ctable pattern that opposing parties rarely find it worthwhile to push their dispute to trial. Using evidence from tort claims across many domains, Ramseyer reveals a court system designed not to find perfect justice, but to “make do”—to adopt strategies that are mostly right and that thereby resolve disputes quickly and economically. An eye-opening study of comparative law, Second-Best Justice will force a wholesale rethinking of the differences among alternative legal systems and their broader consequences for social welfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aActions and defenseszJapan. 0aCivil lawzJapan. 0aLiability (Law)zJapan. 70(DE-601)1060826120(DE-588)4076570-2aRechtswissenschaft2gnd 70(DE-601)10619495X0(DE-588)4047304-1aPrivatrecht2gnd 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  ajapan, japanese, law, legal issues, benefits, beneficial, lawsuits, lawyers, litigation, courtroom, jury, judge, culture, court system, cultural, trial, justice, dispute, conflict resolution, economical, study, welfare, social, community, asia, asian, eastern world, tort, traffic accidents, defense, attorney, liability, products, medical, malpractice, finance, sue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022628199540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226282046423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226282046/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles